Phase 6 sub-chunk 16b-gamma-mount-close (pouch-abort). Overrides musl's
abort() to call _Exit(127) directly instead of reaching a_crash() (a
deliberate NULL deref that musl uses as a last-resort "kill the process"
mechanism after a misbehaved SIGABRT handler returns).

Why the override: at Thylacine v1.0, FAULT_UNHANDLED_USER (an EL0 fault
with no VMA covering the faulting address) extincts the kernel rather
than terminating the offending Proc. a_crash()'s deliberate NULL deref
is therefore not "kill the offending process" but "kill the entire
kernel" -- every assert() / abort() in any pouch program manifests as
boot extinction.

This is the documented v1.x extension in
docs/reference/83-pouch-signals.md ("override pouch's abort.c to _Exit
directly"). Implemented now because P6-pouch-stratumd-boot sub-chunk 16b
needs stratumd's mount-time asserts to fail cleanly instead of taking
the kernel down with them -- without this, the joey stratumd-boot probe
cannot flip from NON-FATAL to FATAL.

Behavioral delta from upstream abort():
  - No raise(SIGABRT). The whole signal-delivery dance (block all sigs,
    install SIG_DFL, tkill, unmask) is removed. Programs that install
    SIGABRT handlers will NOT see them invoked under this abort path.
  - No a_crash() NULL deref. The deliberate fault is replaced with
    _Exit(127), the same status musl reaches at the bottom of its
    abort() path (after raise(SIGKILL) is supposed to kill the process).
  - _Exit(127) routes through SYS_exit_group via the existing pouch
    seam, producing a clean child exit with status 127.

The status code 127 matches musl's normal-termination fallback at the
bottom of abort() (the _Exit(127) past the unreachable a_crash()), so
WIFSIGNALED-vs-WIFEXITED handling is the only observable change for a
parent doing wait_pid. A parent expecting WIFSIGNALED + WTERMSIG ==
SIGABRT (the Linux behavior) will instead see WIFEXITED + WEXITSTATUS
== 127. v1.x will add a sigaction surface that distinguishes the two.

MULTI-THREAD HAZARD (audit-bearing v1.x lift)

The override calls _Exit(127), which routes through pouch's
__NR_exit_group seam (0001-pouch-syscall-seam.patch) to the kernel
SYS_EXITS handler. Kernel-side: if the calling Proc has more than one
live Thread, SYS_EXITS extincts the kernel (the "exits with live peer
threads (caller must join all spawned threads)" check in
kernel/proc.c::exits). Single-thread callers are safe; multi-thread
callers extinct the whole boot.

At v1.0 the safe-use envelope is: abort() may be called only from a
Proc that has spawned no peer threads OR has joined every peer before
the abort. The Thylacine pouch-stratumd-boot 16b-gamma-mount-close
landing satisfies this in the failure mode (stratumd's mount path
runs single-thread; abort there exits cleanly) but does NOT satisfy
this once 16c lands the joey-as-9P-client path (stratumd spawns FS
worker pthreads via serve.c::634 and corvus_notify.c::616, after
which an abort in any thread would take the kernel down).

The proper v1.x fix is a new kernel SYS_EXIT_GROUP that cascades
peer-thread termination via SYS_THREAD_EXIT before transitioning the
Proc to ZOMBIE, with __NR_exit_group wired to it instead of SYS_EXITS.
This is the same primitive needed to close the documented v1.0
"kill in multi-thread Proc returns -EIO" limitation in
audit_p6_pouch_signals_13b_closed_list.md::F9 -- worth lifting as a
focused mini-chunk before 16c.

Until SYS_EXIT_GROUP lands, every multi-thread pouch program must
ensure assertion / abort paths are reachable ONLY pre-thread-spawn
or post-thread-join.

--- a/src/exit/abort.c
+++ b/src/exit/abort.c
@@ -1,30 +1,15 @@
 #include <stdlib.h>
-#include <signal.h>
-#include "syscall.h"
-#include "pthread_impl.h"
-#include "atomic.h"
-#include "lock.h"
-#include "ksigaction.h"

+/* Pouch override (Thylacine P6-pouch-stratumd-boot 16b-gamma-mount-close):
+ * skip raise(SIGABRT) + a_crash() entirely. At v1.0 the kernel extincts
+ * on the deliberate NULL deref a_crash() emits (FAULT_UNHANDLED_USER
+ * policy) -- aborting in any pouch program would take the whole boot
+ * down. _Exit(127) matches musl's normal-termination fallback at the
+ * bottom of upstream abort() (past the unreachable a_crash). v1.x will
+ * add a sigaction(SIGABRT) surface that distinguishes WIFSIGNALED from
+ * WIFEXITED. See docs/reference/83-pouch-signals.md for the design
+ * note. */
 _Noreturn void abort(void)
 {
-	raise(SIGABRT);
-
-	/* If there was a SIGABRT handler installed and it returned, or if
-	 * SIGABRT was blocked or ignored, take an AS-safe lock to prevent
-	 * sigaction from installing a new SIGABRT handler, uninstall any
-	 * handler that may be present, and re-raise the signal to generate
-	 * the default action of abnormal termination. */
-	__block_all_sigs(0);
-	LOCK(__abort_lock);
-	__syscall(SYS_rt_sigaction, SIGABRT,
-		&(struct k_sigaction){.handler = SIG_DFL}, 0, _NSIG/8);
-	__syscall(SYS_tkill, __pthread_self()->tid, SIGABRT);
-	__syscall(SYS_rt_sigprocmask, SIG_UNBLOCK,
-		&(long[_NSIG/(8*sizeof(long))]){1UL<<(SIGABRT-1)}, 0, _NSIG/8);
-
-	/* Beyond this point should be unreachable. */
-	a_crash();
-	raise(SIGKILL);
 	_Exit(127);
 }
